Product: Thermaltake TOUGHRAM RGB DDR4 4000MHz 16GB (8GB x 2) 16.8 Million Color RGB Alexa/Razer Chroma/5V Motherboard Syncable RGB Memory R009D408GX2-4000C19A
Reviews:
['I love the colours and display. Good quality ram.But I really dislike the thermaltake rgb software. It utilises 5% of cpu.', "So I've seen a lot of negative reviews on the 4400Mhz version of this RAM saying that it doesn't work at advertised speeds or clocks and I have to say, those reviews are coming form the uniformed and/or uninitiated. This RAM works perfectly at the advertised speeds and clocks IF you've built the proper system.The best thing you can do for yourself when purchasing ANY RAM is finding the motherboard (MB) you want to use and look at the qualified list of RAM for that MB. It's how I found this RAM, I searched by part number from the authorized list for the MB and saw it was rated for the exact speeds.I've teamed this RAM with an MSI MEG X570 ACE and an AMD Ryzen 9 5900X. My MB manufacturer, MSI, has multiple stages of qualified RAM. For this MB specifically it depends on the series of processor you have. I had to look for the Ryzen 5xxxx series in the qualified list.Wouldn't you know it that when it was all installed, I boot up the system for the first time, go into BIOS, click on the XMP profile button, and it immediately sets the speed and timings to exactly as advertised. That's all you should ever have to do for a properly configured system, 1 click for XMP and that's it, simple. It has been running these exact settings for about 2 weeks now (not a long time, I know, but I'll update if anything happens) and my rig is purring like a kitten.This RAM is great, but you need to know that it works in your board. I know a lot of people have bought this RAM thinking it's essentially painting flames on the side of your car, but it won't make it go any faster. High frequency RAM like this doesn't play well in systems that aren't designed for it. sure it CAN work, but the chances of it working exactly as advertised within a system that hasn't been tested with it is slim to none, and is bound to have issues.Please, please, please do yourselves a favor and do proper research before making purchases on hardware and giving it a bad wrap because you're incompetent. It really does a disservice to others who may want to use the product but sees a bunch of negative reviews when the product itself is fine, it's the person that's the problem.I should probably add that the RAM itself actually looks very nice and I love the heatsink design. The RGB lights on it work very well in my system which is all going in a rainbow pattern. With it being in its default random rainbow wave I've not used any of the software that can control the RAM, but there are plenty of reviews on that elsewhere.Be aware, this RAM is a bit thick due to the quality heatsinks on it, so if you're using an X570 board and an LCS like I am, you may run into issues. I have literally about 1 or 2 mm between my inlet/outlet for my EK AIO 360 and my RAM that is right next to the CPU. Due to the way my system is configured, the layout of the board, and how you have to mount the waterblock I didn't have much choice, but it just barely fits, YMMV but be aware.", "Installation was easy for the hardware.  The memory modules are very solid and manufacturered very well.  The lighting asthetics are really pleasing.  The software, which seems to be a thing with this brand is not very fluid.  For the most part set up of it was fine, but ran into an issue where the lighting wasnt responding to the software.  After days of exstensive searching, i finally contacted tech support.  A few days later we were able to figure out the issue after determining a component of the software didn't install correctly, which goes back to my comments about the software quality being very flakey.  I feel that they could make one app that manages all of the lighting verses multiple programs, but thats a whole different review.  Overall very happy with this purchase and will be looking at another set in the near future.", 'The media could not be loaded.
                



\xa0I like my Thermaltake Arctic 360 and decided to up the ram. It came in a nice box. I never have any problems with them. Customer service is great for me when I have questions.', 'I'd purchased these 4 sets of ram for a build I had been working on, and when I set this system up, I had noticed that a few of my ram sticks were not functioning correctly. I found that the ram with the labelled "DDR4 3600 18-22-22-42" are made differently from other ram on my system. These tended to fail most of the time when attempting to color cycle using any software. The other ram work perfectly fine. This is just a warning to anyone looking to purchase this ram. Even if you are purchasing the same ram, you could end up obtaining a type that is defective. I have had to return two of my four sets due to this issue alone.If you find any that are causing issues like this, return it and get another set that actually work.', 'Patriot Viper Steel Series DDR4 16GB (2 x 8GB) 4400MHz Performance Memory Kit - PVS416G440C9KSo I was reading the prior reviews and thought I would share my experience. Previously I had Patriot Viper Steel DDR4 4400MHz (PVS416G440C9K) and I liked the memory very well but wanted to add RGB to my system and really like the look of these Tough Ram from Thermaltake. My case fans and power supply is from Thermaltake so thought I would give these a shot as I really like their products. I ordered 4 sets (8 sticks) of the Toughram 4400MHz, It was plug and play replacement. Previously I only overclocked the Patriot to 4000MHz as I am a developer and my applications utilized heavily the multicore and wanted to make sure stability is assured as some applications can take a week or more to run. I was able to over clock these to 4000MHz with no issue at all. Unlike other users I have not had an issue at all with the RGB they have worked flawlessly for a week now.I do plan to tinker with the speed to see if I can get to 4400MHz and if I do I will update this post.', "The media could not be loaded.

Will think twice next time I buy from Warehouse.', 'Four 16-GB RAM sticks arrived at a nearby Amazon locker and I was so excited to see what my new 2019 iMac 27" would do with 64 GB of RAM at roughly 1/3 the price of Apple OEM RAM. But my excitement quickly turned to disappointment when the iMac failed to boot with the new RAM. I was ready to prepare a return shipment with Amazon, but decided to call OWC tech support first. After a brief hold, Darrin picked up my call. He said he was in a northwest Chicago suburb and I was grateful for ONSHORE support. Darrin was pleasant, articulate and was clearly not reading off a script. He had me remove the four OWC RAM sticks and wipe the contacts with rubbing alcohol (he first suggested a pencil eraser but I didn\'t have one). While he patiently stayed on the line I wiped the RAM, dried it off, then reinserted the sticks one at a time‚Äì booting the computer with each new stick to see if one of the sticks was faulty. Four sticks installed, four boots‚Äì and 64 GB of RAM counted by my iMac. Darrin says the memory has a lifetime warranty, my support call has been logged, and if the the RAM ever misbehaves in the future it will be replaced. Great customer experience!', 'This took about 3-5 minutes to swap into my 2020 iMac to replace the 8GB that was pre-installed.  One of the easiest installs one could imagine.The difference in performance is noticeable. I had the standard 2020 iMac with 8gb ram. From my basic tasks including multiple browser tabs, Zoom, Outlook, Excel, Powerpoint, and a few others, my performance was almost always being impacted - Zoom being the most noticeable.It seems like I could have gotten away with 16gb, or 32 to leave a good bit of headroom, but I went ahead and got the 64gb which in retrospect might be a bit excessive for all I do, minus the occasional video editing.TLDR: Amazing value for the money - especially compared to apple prices. Super easy to install. Noticeable performance increase if you are a big multitasker or use RAM intensive programs (duh).Image shows a comparison between the stock Apple RAM and the OWC RAM on the bottom.', 'I have read the RAM from OWC (and Crucial) may be the two best brands for upgrading the ram in the 2020 27 inch iMac. My recent experience installing 64 GB of OWC into my machine gives credence to this statement. I have become proficient installing Crucial ram into my computer by only powering it down in place, removing the power cord, installing the ram, then reconnecting the power cord to have the iMac start up and recognize the ram on first try. As this was my first OWC experience I am pleased it went as expected; plus they have a buy back program, just in case I would want to trade-in and upgrade to 128 GB!', 'hace ya casi un a√±o que tengo esa RAM instalada y va de maravillas.']

Reviews: ['Specs were as ordered. Mounted the RAM without any problem!', 'I have a 10 year old MacBook Pro that I‚Äôve recently started using again for some research - mostly web browsing and word processing but also - critically - virtual machines.  The stock 2GB (20% of which reserved for graphics) was just not cutting it.Thankfully these old MBPs are straightforward to upgrade.  I checked the compatibility on Crucial‚Äôs website and ordered the part with Amazon.The upgrade is easy for anybody who can use a screwdriver and follow instructions, but this is going to vary depending on your computer.  It is usually straightforward on most computers, but every now and again you‚Äôll get a particularly awkward model.  It would be worth checking the RAM upgrade procedure for your machine before buying.The RAM has been installed for about a week now and has been working great.  It‚Äôs good practice to check the memory after install, but to be honest a bad module usually gives itself away pretty quickly.  In terms of compatibility, reliability, and price, I don‚Äôt hesitate to buy Crucial memory.', 'Las compr√© para un MacBook Pro 13‚Äù de mediados 2010 y sin problema alguno, totalmente compatibles y f√°ciles de instalar.', "Don't be like me and forget to purchase two LOL! These worked great!.I was able to replace my old RAM without any hesitation thanks to this product and a quick youtube video. I have an iMac and a MacBook Pro. I was constantly staying on my MacBook Pro for all of my picture editing because it was so much faster. But to be perfectly honest I prefer having a larger screen when I am working. Over the past year I had allowed my iMac to become more of a family computer because I am too impatient to wait for a slow computer to get the job done.Finally, I decided to just go for it. I purchased this product and quickly realized I needed two, which was completely my mistake. Once the second one arrived I was ready to trade out my 4GB for 8GB. My computer is now running much faster and I am able to sit down and use both computers to get my work done more quickly and efficiently.In all honesty I recommend if purchasing a Mac go for the lower RAM and just upgrade it yourself to save a pretty penny. 99% of Mac components are amazing but there are definitely some areas that you can save your hard earned money and this is just one of them.", 'Per il mio HP G62 con 2 ram da 2Gb a 1333 (di serie) ho preso due ram Crucial da 4Gb a 1066, arrivando cos√¨ al massimo per il mio notebook, 8Gb. Dal sito Crucial, facendo lo scan, mi dava compatibile quella da 1600, che ho acquistato ma non andava, quindi poco attendibile.Dopo qualche ricerca ho scoperto che avendo un i3-350M ed una scheda madre intel Hm55, potevo avere due banchi da 2Gb a 1333 o due da 4Gb a 1066 o andava in crash il sistema.Consiglio di usare Cpu-Z e verificare il tipo di ram effettiva, se avete la mia stessa configurazione (CPU e MB) con queste andate sul sicuro. Perch√© la frequenza massima supportata resta 1066Mhz.', 'Tenia un netbook Toshiba N305 metido en un cajon, desde hacia ya dos o tres a√±os. Originalmente trae 1 GB de memoria y Windows 7. Con las sucesivas actualizaciones del sistema operativo, y a pesar de haber desactivado multitud de servicios inutiles, desfragmentado y optimizado el disco duro, el pobre ya no podia con el alma. El tiempo de arranque era de 3\', 17" con Windows 7 y de 1\' con Linux Mint 18, 32 bits.  Intentar navegar o abrir cualquier programa con Windows 7, era un suplicio...Primero le puse este modulo de 2 GB (atencion, el mio viene con DDR3)  y actualic√© el sistema operativo a Windows 10, 32 bits. Su espiritu ha resucitado y es totalmente utilizable con Windows. Su tiempo de arranque ha bajado a 1\' 6".Viendo el resultado, me anim√© y le cambi√© el disco duro original por un SSD Samsung Evo de 120 GB. Su velocidad ha triplicado, navegar es un placer. Tiempo de arranque 24" con Windows 10. Todavia no he instalado Linux, pero supongo que ir√† como un tiro. Un saludo.', "I was truly about ready to trash my once-beloved Macbook Pro.  Spending hours every day waiting while the dreaded rainbow wheel spun on the monitor was really bringing me down and killing my efficiency.  Enter the Crucial (in more ways than one) RAM upgrade.  My swap was running in the neighborhood of 2.5 gb at any given time, even with no applications running; it is now ZERO!  I cannot believe that I tolerated the slowness for so long.  I thought I was just waiting for my Mac to die, and a drawn-out, agonizing death it was going to be.  I currently have six open tabs in Safari going, as well as iTunes, which I could NEVER run in the background prior to this upgrade.  Web pages are loading lightning-quick and I can switch between/among applications instantly.  Before, I had to wait for what seemed like forever for tabs and applications *to close*.  This is amazing.  I've been contacting my Mac-owning friends all day to tell them about this quick and inexpensive fix for their computer woes.  Additionally, I had my Mac open, cleaned, RAM swapped, and everything put back together in about 5 minutes.  Highly recommended.", 'I ordered one like this off ebay and my computer crashed, because the one the person that owned it before me had in it was not the correct type. It was 1000, when this is 1066, what I needed. So I got rid of the junk one and the one identical to this showed a faster memory rating on the Window info. So I ordered this one to match the one I got that was correct. The one I got on ebay said Made in USA, too bad this one says Made in China, yet it is the same memory stick. And I had to pay a lot more for it too.  But it works great with the other one to give my laptop 8 gigs of DDR3 ram. It would have been 5* if it was "Made in USA". :-)', "Normally, I would post a list of pros and cons for a product I'm reviewing however this review is specifically for users of Synology based products. I own a Synology DS1813+ network attached storage appliance ( NAS ). In a nutshell, the Crucial 2GB DDR3 1066 MT/s (PC3-8500) CL7 SODIMM 204-pin memory memory works perfectly in my unit.I created this review because my search for a compatible memory module was limited in that the Synology website - while it listed the compatible settings for the memory I needed, it didn't list compatible memory manufacturers. I felt I should contribute my findings for other users looking for similar memory.Installation was a breeze, shutdown the unit, remove the top cover (attached with small phillips head screws), install the new module, and finally verify the memory was recognized by the system after rebooting.  Up-time has only been a few days but I'm experiencing no issues whatsoever.Finally, remember to use anti static precautions when you install,I home this review helps!", 'Super easy and quick to install. Takes literally less than a minute.Definitely perked up my ten year old iMac. After downloading a newer OS, it ran sooo slow, it was pathetic. With the new RAM installation, it was back to what I was used to.  Much better than shelling out bucks for a new one since I have older Adobe Creative Suites installed which probably wouldn‚Äôt even work on a new Mac and I will never "rent" Photoshop and Illustrator considering I‚Äôm older, retired and only use these softwares a very few times a year, mainly pro bono work for church and charities.I use my iPad dail...my old iMac mainly sits unused.  So thank you Crucial.']

\xa0First off-I am able to run my Ryzen 2700x on an X370 Mb at 3600mhz....which shouldn't work. Previously, with Samsung B-die I was limited to 3200mhz. My machine would run 3400mhz with the B-die but was not stable. I have not fully tested the stability of these at 3600 yet but so far after Cinebench a few times and 3dmark...no crashes and no errors.Likes:This Micron memory is extremely friendly to Ryzen cpuI love the low profile heatsink that includes RBG...they are the same height as Ballistix non-rbg memory.I've just been running the RBG in asynchronous mode so far but I like it that way and the colors are sharp and not muted or muddled; they look really good.32GB  for 2 sticks of  16 GB each.Dislikes:??? Nothing so far.Other:Amazon lost the first package so it was never delivered. It was supposed to be a 1 day delivery. The second order was two days and that's fine, at least it got here.I can't say enough about these Micron modules. I had 16GB DDR4 36000 Trident Z modules that would not run this speed on my system at all. I am shocked that the Ballistix are able to do so. My limitation right now is the motherboard, but I'd love to upgrade the MB and see how far I could overclock these babies. Your mileage may vary, but for me and my Ryzen system, this memory is the best!", 'XMP 2.0 instantly registers correctly on an MSI X470 Gaming Carbon Pro with a Ryzen 7 3700X.I used DRAM CALCULATOR and tweaked the timing tighter to 16-16-16-36  (CL-RCD-RP-RAS) on 1.3V and these are the best performing DRAM modules I have ever owned - HANDS DOWN.They are at least as good (if not better) than Samsung B-die and are high quality Micron released in week 20 of 2020 and can keep up with any Ryzen 7/9  on any X470/X570/B550/B450 platform.Temps stay really low.  Great quality heat sinks, and Crucial has an app that will turn on any color of the rainbow.  I use their app to turn off the RGB completely (which is what you will need to install if you want to turn off the RGB).  I did not use the RGB.  It come on pulsating by default.This is the most reliable DDR4 3600 DRAM you can get for the price as of Fall/2020.  The reason it is out of stock all the time is because it does exactly what it says it will do and is rock steady DRAM at the advertised speeds.  Very easy to O/C this dram, but recommend at least the X470/X570/B550 VRMs for O/C.FAST! on the Ryzen 3700X @ 4.3Ghz', "Bien que certains recherchent du rouge en priorit√©, je dois admettre que ce n'est pas quelque chose qui m'importe, √©tant donn√© que mon pc est ferm√©.Le produit est de bonne facture et je n'ai aucune instabilit√©, donc si vous voyez qu'une couleur est moins ch√®re que les autres, n'h√©sitez pas!", "Gigabyte AORUS compatibility list has these listed as a dual rank sticks. That does not seem to be the case based on CPUZ readings. Although it does seems to hit the other numbers with XMP turned on. I downloaded the software to manage the colors, and it doesn't work. Tried managing the colors with the software from Gigabyte as well, but nothing changed. So, not sure what is happening there. Looks like there may be an error log file suggesting the MoBo is not compatible. That seems odd considering is says it is compatible with the Gigabyte AORUS and I run the 570X Ultra. Want just a solid color. So, lots of money for some sticks that seem to not be what expected. Not the fault of this listing for the rank issue, but so far not thrilled with the support software for these sticks on top of it. Just letting you Gigabyte folks know there could be issues.", 'mein lieblings RAM f√ºr Ryzen, leider wird er immer teurer', 'Worked great with my Ryzen 5800x and previously, my 3700x. Ram runs at advertised XMP profile with zero issues. Head spreaders seem to work well as the ram runs cooler than my previous set (Corsair Vengeance RGB pro).Downside? RGB isnt as pretty as corsair, and my Asus Aura sync on my Crosshair Dark Hero motherboard will not recognize it. So i have to use Gigabyte RGB software to control the ram.', 'Replaced my 16GB 3000 MHz set with this, and it worked straight out of the box with XMP on my MSI B450-A PRO mobo on AGESA 1.2.0.5 with a 5800X. I wish the RGB lights would be synced by itself, but SignalRGB fixed that for me.Can confirm these are dual rank as well.', "I think I should bring this to the attention of everyone. These modules (2x16) are now single rank modules. You can tell when you get the package - it says M8FB1 which means its the Micron Rev B dies and not the Micron Rev E dies. Therefore Micron has effectively transitioned to making their 16gb modules as single rank and moved away from the Dual Rank that most of us are seeking. I ordered 3 of these sets - one from the actual Crucial website and 2 from amazon; all 3 are the single rank Rev B dies. I'm going to return all 3 and get the dual rank Gskillz Ripjaw V. Shame, I would have loved to have the Micron Rams in the my system.....", "I'm satisfied. Overclocking is applied more than XMP settings. This is a good 32GB DRAM that can be purchased under $200.One unfortunate thing is that I'm curious about the difference in yield between Micron E-Die and B-Die. I got a B-die."]

Product: Crucial RAM 64GB Kit (2x32GB) DDR5 5600MHz (or 5200MHz or 4800MHz) Laptop Memory CT2K32G56C46S5
Reviews: ["My laptop originally arrived with only 16GB DDR5 RAM, and Windows 11 required just over half that for itself.  I needed a lot more for flight simulation, truck simulation, and VR games (not to mention productive tasks, lol).  Laptop BIOS adjusted the memory itself, no need to remember what that special key is to do it manually.  Everything from booting up to running apps is a lot faster, and I don't have to worry about apps crashing because they maxed out the memory.  It's perfect for my mid-level gaming laptop!  Easy for me to install, though I do have a lot of experience upgrading and repairing computers and laptops.  Lots of YouTube videos to teach how to install in just about any laptop it is designed for, and computer tools are fairly inexpensive now.  If you are up for upgrading yourself (or have a teen at home, lol), this is definitely worth every penny.", "I have the Acer Predator 240Hz 16 inch, 4080, intel i9 -13900HX. It came stock with 16GB of 5600 RAM. I like to game and I also run a lot of virtual machines (but not while I'm gaming). The RAM I bought to upgrade was 64GB @5600. When I installed it, it only ran at 4800. This wasn't Crucial's fault. Acer limits advance settings in the BIOS so you can't change the clock speed. I though, ok no biggie, a few less FPS won't kill my game play, but then my games kept crashing (not the laptop itself). They crashed every 15 - 20 mins and I did tested multiple games. I removed the new RAM and put stock RAM back in and had no issues. I would have kept the RAM if it had not crashed my games constantly.Lesson's learned: Make sure the laptop manufacture can support the ability to change the clock speeds in the BIOS. Acer unfortunately doesn't support this feature.", "Honestly i didn't notice much improvement in speed compared to 4800 MT/s i previously had", 'Installed these SODIMM modules in a Minisforum UM790 Pro mini PC, which supports DDR5-5600 RAM. They work great! :D', 'bought a bare bones pa and this memory is awesome', 'Works perfect... Quick...', 'Turned my Razer 18 into a 64gig beast- also added a fast 4tB Nvme drive .', 'Either stick works if installed individually in my Asus 7945hx laptop, but both sticks would cause occasional BSOD if installed together. Both Memtest86 and Memtest86+ show >10000 errors.Returned both sticks, and now have to find another compatible pair.', "j'ai mon pc acer predator avec un i9 13 gen qui prend la m√©moire a 5600mhz, et la je regarde les crusial sont reconnue en 4800mhz ...... se sont les barrette le souci", 'As others have stated, the ram isn‚Äôt 5600 it shows up as 5200. It also is unstable as can be, constant windows crashes and blue screens. Finally ram memtest86 to make sure it wasn‚Äôt an OS issue and sure enough, the test aborted after just 30 minutes or so with over 10,000 memory errors.Save your trouble and your money, don‚Äôt bother purchasing.For reference I‚Äôm running an intel i7-13850HX in a Dell Precision 7680 laptop.Will be finding replacement memory elsewhere.']

Product: Crucial DDR5-5200 UDIMM CL42 16GBIT RAM, 32GB (2 x 16GB)
Reviews: ['„É°„Éº„Ç´„Éº„ÅÆ„É™„Çπ„Éà„Å´„ÅØ„Å™„ÅÑ„É°„É¢„É™„Åß„Åó„Åü„Åå„ÄÅASrock B650 Pro RS(BIOS1.24)„ÅßÂãï‰Ωú„Åó„Åæ„Åó„Åü„ÄÇ„Åü„Å†„ÄÅ‰ª•‰∏ã„ÅÆ„É°„É¢„É™Ë®≠ÂÆö„Å†„Å®„Éë„ÇΩ„Ç≥„É≥„ÅåËêΩ„Å°„Åü„Çä„ÄÅ„Éñ„É´„Éº„Çπ„ÇØ„É™„Éº„É≥„Åå„Åß„Åæ„Åó„Åü„ÄÇ„Éª„Éû„Ç∂„ÉúÂà∂Âæ°„ÅÆAUTO(‚ñ≥)„Åü„Åæ„Å´PC„ÅåËêΩ„Å°„Åæ„Åó„Åü„ÄÇ„Éª„É°„É¢„É™Ë®≠ÂÆö„ÅÆ„Éá„Éï„Ç©„É´„Éà5200(‚ñ≥)„Ç®„É©„Éº„Åå1ÂõûËµ∑„Åç„Åæ„Åó„Åü„ÄÇÁèæÂú®„ÅØEXPO-5200„ÅÆË®≠ÂÆö„Åß‰ΩøÁî®„Åó„Å¶„ÇÇ‰∏çÂÖ∑Âêà„ÅØ‰∏ÄÂàá„Å™„ÅÑ„Åß„Åô„ÄÇ', "This item has been with me for a very short time.So, here's the thing. I recently decided to upgrade my computer because it was struggling to keep up with my demanding multitasking and gaming needs. After doing some extensive research, I came across Crucial RAM 32GB Kit (2x16GB) DDR5 Memory and boy, am I excited about it! Firstly, the 32GB capacity is a game-changer for me as it allows me to run resource-intensive applications smoothly without any lag. And let's not forget about the fact that this RAM kit utilizes DDR5 technology, which provides faster data transfer rates and improved power efficiency compared to its predecessors. This means quicker load times, snappier response times, and overall better performance of my system. Additionally, Crucial has a solid reputation for delivering reliable and high-quality products. All in all, ordering this Crucial RAM 32GB Kit (2x16GB) DDR5 Memory was a no-brainer choice for me as it promises to drastically enhance my computing experience!I hope you find this review helpful.", 'This one popped up on my recommended list.  I looked at the listing, saw that it won\'t fit my computer and closed it.  Or so I thought.  Must\'ve been dozing off or something.  I\'ve had the itch to build a new system, but mine is pretty up to date for what I use it, (gaming for me is Freecell) and I don\'t have anyone in my circle of acquaintances who wants a new system.  Anyway, I may build what Boeing would call a "white tail."  One without a customer just to keep the lines busy.So how can I fairly review this product?  Crucial is Micron\'s finished product line.  Unless you\'re a chip-head like me, that may not mean much, but Micron memory chips are among the best.  I\'ve used their SSDs (including the one in the computer on which I\'m writing this) and RAM and have never had an issue.  I\'m a huge fan.  Several famous brands use Micron chips; when you look on the QVL of most motherboards it will tell you the chip brand and Micron is quite popular.  Looking at these through the package, they look typical first tier quality.  Good solder, good plating on the edge contacts and the chips line up on the boards. Sounds like a low bar, but not really.So to make up for not being able to fairly judge the performance, I thought that I would look up a few popular motherboards\' QVL and report.  AM5 motherboards using the B650 chipset.  For a hobbyist building a mid-grade system, that\'s what I would recommend.  If you want the latest, that is.  Checking popular motherboards from AS Rock, Asus, Gigabyte and MSI, none of them had this set on their list.  What?  Checking the Crucial website, there is a compatibility checker with drop down menus that is a LOT less frustrating than the motherboard manufacturers\' lists.  Every board that I had previously checked that didn\'t have these listed was compatible.  I can\'t officially say that they will work, I can\'t officially say that they won\'t.  But as a guess, probably yes.  Of course, that\'s the problem with a QVL.  If a particular device isn\'t on the list, does it mean that it was tested and didn\'t pass or was it just not tested?  There are about 13 zillion models of RAM sticks and substantially fewer motherboards, so if it\'s on the list for the memory but not the motherboard, most likely the motherboard manufacturer just didn\'t test it.Bottom line?  A Good Product from a Great Brand.  Even though I can\'t test these particular sticks, based on previous experience with Crucial and a visual inspection, I would highly recommend them.', 'Since Micron has thrown out the Ballistix branding (which was the special faster memory Micron has had for a while), Micron\'s consumer DDR5 under Crucial has been these memory sticks, it\'s very generic looking, but at least the PCB is black, so your build wouldn\'t look absolutely horrible.These are what I thought would be the equivalent of "3200mhz JEDEC DDR4 memory that doesn\'t have any XMP profiles and run at the stock 1.2V", however these things have XMP and EXPO profiles, which is not something that more generic DDR4 had. This means you can take advantage of improved performance, especially on AMD. Just keep in mind that if you do enable EXPO, you probably should make sure your BIOS is up-to-date otherwise depending on which brand of motherboard you have (especially ASUS), your CPU might explode because of a BIOS voltage flaw, that\'s been corrected by newer BIOS.(I don\'t know if your performance changes if you say, use XMP on AMD and EXPO on Intel, it\'s probably better to stick to EXPO on AMD and XMP on Intel when you select your memory profile in the BIOS)Because it\'s DDR5 it has a lot of telemetry that can be read from in HWInfo, similar to older DDR4 modules, you can actually read the temperature. Now, I assume given the relatively tame performance these don\'t necessarily need extra cooling and therefore doesn\'t have any heatspreaders. I don\'t know how well these can overclock, but if you do, maybe having some extra airflow might help if you\'re doing something crazy. I know when Crucial first launched these, the reason they discontinued Ballistix was because they couldn\'t hit higher performance memory, maybe since it\'s been a while these will actually overclock better?Overall, these are excellent if you\'re doing a SFF build. The standard module height gives you lots of space for either cooler clearance or space for cables. Previously Corsair had their LPX memory, but since Corsair hasn\'t released their LPX memory for DDR5, these are a good option. I\'m using it with a Gigabyte B650i in a Lian Li A4 h2o, and the daughterboard on the motherboard means that the lower height from these memory make cable management for the 24pin just a little bit easier. I think these are also good if you have something like a Noctua NH-D15, these will give enough clearance for that CPU cooler.', "Micron is top notch and their Crucial Line has always served me well. Sure, 5200 might not be the fastest DDR5 but it's more than enough for any 12th Gen Intel and, frankly, probably better than running faster DRAM from a less reliable bargain brand. In real world terms, this is plenty fast for basically anybody.", 'These ram are great for DDR5 builds as they are very low profile and works with all SFF cases. You must enable XMP to get the full 5200MT/s out of any DDR5 kits to get the advertised speed. They have been very stable while gaming and any tasks. Would recommend for a budget PC build using Ryzen 7000!', "DDR5 memory has really come down in price this year. This is a nice dual stick of memory set that works well in my system. It's not flashy with RGB, and since I can't see the inside of my PC anyway I'm fine with that. Overall, this is a real bargain and you get genuine Crucial memory for a great price.", "The Crucial 32GB (2x16GB) DDR5 5200MHz kit with model number CT2K16G52C42U5 is best suited for OEM systems like your Alienware R15s, or your Lenovo Legion T7s etc.  The CAS latency is slowed down here at 42 and it's more compatible with those OEM motherboards than aggressive kits that uses lower timings like 36 and 38.  They will also allow you to enable XMP properly on those systems.For custom builds, it will also work.  For instance, it works with the MSI MPG Z690 Edge Wifi (DDR5 model) but it's not good value.  For the same price or lower, you can get compatible kits with faster speed (5600MHz, 6000MHz), faster timings (C36), cool looking heat spreaders and the cherry on top, RGB bling. You should check against the Qualified Vendor List (QVL) from your motherboard's support page to see what memory kits are supported to maximize your return on investment.  The Crucial kit is a last resort.In summary, if you have an OEM built system that uses DDR5, this memory upgrade kit is your best chance at finding a working one.  Everyone else should look at other options that are not only cheaper but also faster.", "These sticks of ddr5 ram went into my computer perfectly and work as intended. I don't have any benchmarks other than it plugs in and works, but I would recommend this as a more economical source of ram.", "This RAM kit from Crucial requires no introduction and they work as expected without issues. I have no problems with 'em running at 5200 MHz as specified; however, they do run a bit hotter/warmer than usual in comparison to others that I have. I've run PRIME95 for quite a few hours without any issues either so that's a good sign. Btw, they are 42-42-42-84-126 for those who are wondering.‚â° ValueAll things considered, these are decent RAM modules that work as expected without issues; however, they are also a bit pricey at $205 for 2x16G DDR5 @ 5200Mhz in comparison to some others. These can be as much as 30-45% more expensive than other brands with identical spec so you do have quite a few options and alternatives out there.I built (aka assembled) my first PC back in the latest 80's (with a 20 MB hard disk) and based on my experience so far memory modules usually fail (if they do) VERY early on (days, hours, or even minutes) and seldom weeks or months afterwards so if they pass the stress tests (PRIME95 or any other ones available to you) for 24-48 hours, they are generally good and should outlast any components in a PC that have mechanical movements. My point being, many options exist for these memory modules if you care to try."]

Reviews: ['ÂïèÈ°å„Å™„Åè‰ΩøÁî®„Åß„Åç„Åæ„Åó„Åü', Product: SABRENT Rocket DDR5 16GB U-DIMM 4800MHz Memory Module for Desktops and PCs (SB-DR5U-16G)
Reviews: ['The ram works and does increase the performance on my gaming PC. You can use this single stick alone as it is 16 GB. Sabrent has yet to disappoint me and I consider it a trusted brand. I do not have to worry about it being bad ram. After several months of using this ram, I have not seen any issues with this device. The specification for this ram is as followed 16 GB DDR5 4800 Mhz. In terms of gaming, this can work for that purpose. I would recommend at least 16 gb  and this works great. You do not need multiple sticks for 16 gb.. I put this into my new gaming PC and it works pretty well. I personally like the simple look of it and the heatsink keeps it from over heating. It is little heavier and thicker due to heatsink plating.  If you are planning to use this as a single stick in your desktop, this will work really well. 16 gb can run a gaming PC pretty well but it still bare minimum. It is pretty easy to install. One thing to note is that you should unplug your computer before changing the ram. Also make sure that you discharge yourself (touch metal) before handling to avoid static damage. It does not require any additional installation or setting changes (at least on my end) to make this work. Again the most important thing is to make sure you unplug your computer from the power before you install this to avoid any problems. It is just simple ram that has a pretty fast performance. It provides me with the ram I needed my gaming needs. It is also little more future proof. As a single stick, it is more than enough ram to surf the web, watch videos, and such. Be aware that for most gaming computers, 16 gb minimum is recommended. There are no real heating issues with a heat sink. It performs pretty well.  Overall this is a very decently performing DDR5 ram. It performances is strong. It is great as a single stick of 16 gb. You can use this to added ram to a gaming PC or just use it in a new computer build as a single stick. It will work great.', "I use Sabrent for my SD card, CF express cards, and DDR4 SODIMM sticks and have found that their presentation and quality for their products is generally a tier above the rest. This DDR5 stick is no exception - it worked fine on my low-power 12th-gen 1u build. The ram has no problem sitting at 4800MHz and hasn't had any memory-related issues with my computer build.Overall, pretty simple stick that performs as expected - it's expensive, but it's DDR5", 'This Sabrent 4800 mhz DDR5 ram is good enough to play with for an early adopter of the technology, but personally I would probably wait for decreased prices and increasing stability as the tech is employed in more mainstream consumer products. In a few years, DDR5 will be far more mainstream, and the price will be further in line with the demand, which is currently limited to tech enthusiasts.If you are going to go this route, absolutely get a second stick to pair it with. Dual channel will significantly increase your computing power, but keep in mind that DDR5 is a bit more power hungry than DDR4 and you will also need the right mobo/cpu combo to work with it.All of that said, competitors already have 5000+ mhz listed for similar and/or lower prices, and that makes this a bit pricier than it needs to be, even with the current market niche it occupies. Stability with DDR5 will continue to improve as user metrics come in and manufacturers continue to incorporate it into their newer builds.', "This Sabrent rocket ddr5 module is fantastic (albeit pricey)! I have used many Sabrent m.2 drives and was wondering when they'd get into the ddr5 game. Now that they are here I am not disappointed! for the price (at time of acquiring) this was a great deal on a 16gb module, But now at the time of review, you can get 32gb sets for the same price. Although this is very quality ram, for the Speed and Latency I would wait for the price to come down before purchasing.", "An interesting stick of ram. I own many Sabrent items, having used their memory card for years I was excited to try out their new entry to the ram market. These sticks didn't disappoint so to say but they are lacking XMP profiles, which for many people who don't know how to or choose not to manually overclock ram, could be a deal breaker.These sticks do like to overclock, quite well, I was able to get 6000Mhz at 1.4 volts with timings of 36-36-36-77 to run extremely stable. The memory modules are good units, SK Hynix M-dies and the controller is the pretty much industry standard Renesas P8911, that most everyone uses.Overall they have functioned flawlessly under everything I throw at them running at 6000Khz with an I9-12900K and rock solid for stabality. A great stick of ram, and I assume as time passes and Sabrent grows their ram line we will see on board XMP profiles.", "It's good to see the price of DDR5 going down, although don't expect to go down to the cost of DDR4 soon. This 16GB module from Sabrent is equipped a heatsink, which helps for high performance applications like gaming. This isn't the fastest DDR5, but it is 1.5x the speed of 3200MHz which is still the default speed of DDR4. I noticed a pretty decent performance uplift when using this single stick, when compared to 2x8GB sticks of 3200MHz that I was using with an Intel Core i5 (12th gen).Just make sure you need this latest type of RAM when you are shopping for 12th generation Intel motherboards, unless you're buying for Ryzen 7000, in which case you won't have a choice.", "I have a lot of time for Sabrent. I trust their SD and CFExpress cards with my most important photos, so I have no problem at all handing them the job of running the RAM in my desktop. As expected this module was a piece of cake to install, my system recognised it immediately, and after a couple of weeks of use I've had absolutely no issues with it. I'd be amazed to have any issues, to be honest. Sabrent is a rock solid brand.My only slight complaint with this module is the price. I recently installed 2x16GB DDR5 4800MHz RAM modules from Corsair into my laptop, and the pair cost $230 ( on sale from $275). This single 16GB module from Sabrent, on the other hand, currently sells at $180 (on sale from $280). I consider Sabrent among the best of the best but I also rate Corsair pretty highly, and I find it hard to justify the significantly higher price for the Sabrent modules.As far as performance is concerned, though, I couldn't be happier.", "This SABRENT Rocket DDR5 16GB U-DIMM RAM runs at speeds of up to 4800MHz. To make the most of this RAM you'll want a MOBO that supports DDR5 RAM and you may want to consider purchasing another stick to run it in dual channel mode.I purchased a 2nd stick of this  SABRENT Rocket DDR5 16GB U-DIMM RAM to use in a Ryzen 9 build that centered around an ASUS ROG Strix Z690-F Gaming MOBO. This memory is blazing fast! The 16GB module is the smallest size most that's useful in mid to high-end builds.What I liked most about this SABRENT Rocket DDR5 16GB U-DIMM RAM was:- Fast- Good price-to-performance- Negligible thermal impact- Doesn't interfere with most CPU cooler installsWhat I liked least about this SABRENT Rocket DDR5 16GB U-DIMM RAM was:- Price fluctuations may mean you'll get better price-to-performance at some times over others. However, that's the nature of PC parts in generalOverall, if you're building a new mid to high-end system then this SABRENT Rocket DDR5 16GB U-DIMM RAM should be on your shortlist. This SABRENT Rocket DDR5 16GB U-DIMM RAM is fast, reliable, and offers good price-to-performance. It fit within my Ryzen system without interfering with the stock air cooler that came with my Ryzen CPU or the AIO I added shortly thereafter. I did find the price a bit cheaper when I purchased the 2nd module than it was when I first received this one to review. However, that's not SABRENT's fault so much as it is the nature of PC components. 4.5 out of 5.0", "This looks akin to their NVMe ssd drives, with a thin heat spreader in the same design fashion. I am happy to report that it is good ram, but really doesn't stand out in the crowd. It looks good next to the Sabrent heatsink/spreader design which seems very similar across the board for them.The issue here is, while good, this is not a very competitive price even on sale. 180ish on sale and you get 16gb of ram. For 200, you get Corsair Vengeance ram at 2x16GB and 5200mhz. I like the look here better, but it is not the best value is all I am trying to say. I still think it is worth 4 stars though!", 'DDR5 is a new animal (but then again, so were DDR4 and DDR3 before it‚Ä¶) - with much higher RAM speeds and much higher memory bandwidths, it removes some of the prior bottlenecks that were starting to show up on now legacy DDR4 powered platforms.  Generally, this means that you get even faster performance which is always a good thing.Here you get a 16GB stick which is a good size - I‚Äôd always generally recommend going with dual channel (an even number of matched sticks - if your board supports it) so would say you should have either 2 or 4 of these, meaning you‚Äôd have 32GB or 64GB of RAM which is quite a good bit for usage today.  It‚Äôs largely going to be a drop in (well, click in) upgrade installation and you should be good to go if your setup supports DDR5.Price-wise, this is in line with what I would expect for DDR5 at the time of writing this review - it‚Äôs newer technology and starting to be in demand, particularly in the power-user crowd.  Combine that with ongoing chip shortages AND that DDR5 requires additional power/compute chips than prior member standards and you have a recipe for higher prices.  So this is a reasonable price for the time and what you get.All that is to say - if you have a platform that supports DDR5, this is a pretty good DDR5 module to get - I‚Äôve had good luck with accessories and components from Sabrent and this seems to be no different.  Well worth a try if you‚Äôre in the market for DDR5 memory.']

Reviews: ['Great product. Looks very nice. Hate RGB lights but this looks really good.', "If you're doing an RGB themed build then stay away from Thermaltake.  I hate to say it but I've never been more disappointed in Thermaltake.  I run a thirty year old computer repair shop and I've faithfully used standard Thermaltake products for many years with pride.  I will no longer offer anything from Thermaltake at my store nor will I ever purchase anything for stock from them ever again.  All manufacturers these days offer such similar products that the support and reliability are ultimately what separate them.  Thermaltake has failed us miserably.  To go in the View 31 RGB Dual Tempered Glass case we have gone with the Thermaltake UX100 RGB CPU Heatsink/Fan, a 16GB Thermaltake TOUGHRAM kit, a Thermaltake RGB 750W TOUGHPOWER Grand Series PSU.  We were planning on using the pre-installed Riing 14 case fans that had factored into our purchase decision originally, but after two RMA's for the included fan controller (the original had brightness issues that were NEVER resolved, the first replacement they sent was just the incorrect part, second replacement changed nothing) and zero solutions we upgraded to the aftermarket Pure Plus 14 RGB Premium three fan kit and controller because I'm pretty reasonable and loyal.  Nice fan kit by the way, but it would only be appropriate if it was to be your ONLY RGB feature.  There is no syncing between all of these products despite Thermaltake expressly boasting that there is.  After the email thread from support reached 25 emails and after we have spent hundreds of dollars and after several hours of labor troubleshooting and after we have tried motherboards from multiple manufacturers on both the Intel and AMD platforms, we have decided to warn everyone we can to stay away from Thermaltake RGB products.", 'Funcionan de maravilla', 'For 2 sticks of ddr4 ram these really do pop with the rgbs. They are very bright and accurate colors. Thermaltake has always been a go to brand for quality hence the more expensive pricing normally but these were priced on sale same as some inferior brands so i had to swoop them up. NO ISSUES whatsoever. Worked right out the package no fuss. They stay col and the latency and everything is as advertised. My only complaint is very minor. If you just leave the ram as is with no system integrated rgb controller then they dont sync up. They wil start showing the same colors at the same time but after a minute or so one will get ahead of the other and they wil no longer be matched up in their color cycle.. Thats the only con though', 'When I bought it, the 3600MHZ was cheaper than the 3200MHZ. The ram sticks work as expected, though the RGB software for the ram sticks is glitchy.Pros:Lots of rgbFast speedsSlick designCons:RGB software is glitchy and crashes', "It's alright, the ram does the job it's supposed to. The design is very elegant, wat above average. But at that price point, you'd expect the RGB to be higher quality. There are only 5 LEDs and the software to manage them is quite archaic. Returning them to get higher performance ram without RGB for cheaper.", 'The Thermaltake Z-one ram looks great.  It has an industrial look and feel to it with the brushed aluminum on top and the black casing.  It‚Äôs low profile so it‚Äôs great for cases that do not have a lot of head room and you maybe want to run an aio at the top.  No issues enabling xmp and ram string at 3600mhz', 'Good ram, good build quality, CAS and freq meet specs.  XMP works great.  Fantastic if you have ThermalTake RGB software.  Syncs great with the fans and other items.  All in all for a TT build I say go for it.  The price is comparable to any other RGB ram so all in all good product and price.', 'They look great and they work great. I had zero issues.My build:CPU: AMD Ryzen 7 3700XMotherboard: MSI MPG Gaming Edge with WifiMemory: 16GB DDR4 3200MHz RGBStorage 1: Samsung 500GB M.2 NVMEStorage 2: Seagate Barracuda 2TB HDDGPU: NVIDIA GeForce RTX 2070 Super 8GBPSU: 750W 80+ Gold with RGBCase: MUSETEX ATX Mid-tower 903-D6', 'worth for the price']

['Hola que tal amigos la verdad es que las memorias estan a otro nivel, la calidad de construcci√≥n es inigualable, las tengo montadas con un ryzen 9 5950x en una MB ASRock 570 Taichi Razer Edition, al igual que muchos de aqui fue un problema subirlas de frecuencia dado que el xmp que viene por defecto no funciona y es necesario ir subiendo de a poco a poco el voltaje para ver hasta que punto pueden hacer funcionar las memorias, las mias directamente mi intuici√≥n me dice que no tienen esa loter√≠a de hacerles un OC extremo , le pude aumentar las frecuencias de momento hasta los 3566 MHZ con un voltaje de 1.368 lo cual me da una tempera en solo las memorias ram de 38¬∞C teniendolas en un gabinete Asus Rog Helios  lo cual considero que sea bueno, intentare subirle un poco la frecuencia haber cuanto voltaje se necesita para llevarlas a lo mencionado con el fabricante pero de antemano les menciono para ryzen es falso que funcionen a 1.35v de stock de ahi en mas las latencias son buenas de 16-17-16-34-50 y compar√°ndolas contra otras memorias que cabe decir son mas baratas con un latencias de 16-20-20 creo que estas son mejores no por mucho pero te puedes ahorrar unos minutos en renders, a la hora de editar un video en full hd con efectos de 28 min se pudo lograr en 18min por lo que recomiendo estas memorias solo si el dinero no es problema para ustedes, cabe destacar que las garant√≠as corsair son de primer nivel y se hacen responsables de sus productos en toda latinoam√©rica, espero que mi review les haya gustado no hay mucha informaci√≥n en espa√±ol.', 'The media could not be loaded.
                



\xa0Die Rezension bezieht sich auf Corsair Dominator Platinum RGB 64GB (4x16GB) 3600MHz C16 ‚Äì schwarz. Verbaut sind die Riegel in einem ASUS Dark Hero mit einem AMD Ryzen 5950x Prozessor.Die Lieferung war wie immer sehr schnell (Amazon) und die versiegelte Neuware kam gut verpackt und unbesch√§digt an. Die Module f√ºhlen sich schwer und wertig an ‚Äì aus diesem Material h√§tte ich gerne ein Geh√§use, Corsair.Ich habe mich aus Performance Gr√ºnden (AMD Ryzen 5000 Generation) f√ºr die 4x16 Version entschieden. Hierbei muss jeder mit sich selbst ausmachen, ob das einem den Preis f√ºr C16 wert ist. Man darf nicht vergessen, dass man sich f√ºr die knapp ‚Ç¨1.200 schon einen Komplettrechner zulegen kann. Alle paar Jahre baue ich mir ein neues System und gehe daher keine Kompromisse ein.Im BIOS habe ich f√ºr erste Tests das D.O.C.P Profil ausgew√§hlt und die Riegel haben "out oft he box" stabil unter 3.600MHz funktioniert. Es gibt zwar ein wenig Overclocking Spielraum, 4.000 MHz konnte ich stabil, unter vern√ºnftigen Rahmenbedingungen, jedoch nicht erreichen. Mehr Module = weniger Spielraum.Tip: Stabilit√§tstests bitte immer z.B. mit MemTest86 (kostenlos) vom gebooteten USB-Stick durchf√ºhren ‚Äì alle anderen Methoden (unter Windows) sind untauglich und funktionieren nicht.Ein weiterer Grund f√ºr die Anschaffung war die M√∂glichkeit zur direkten Steuerung √ºber iCUE 4.x. Mein komplettes System ist sehr Corsair lastig (1000D, Commander Pro, Lightning Nodes, RGB Hubs, LQ 120/140 L√ºfter, etc.). Wer darauf keinen Wert legt sollte sich die Anschaffung gut √ºberlegen, da der Preis schon wirklich beachtlich ist. Die C17er von Trident gibt es f√ºr weniger als die H√§lfte, C18er von Corsair gibt es in dieser Konfiguration f√ºr gut ‚Ç¨600...Wirklich empfehlen kann ich den RAM normalen Anwendern nicht. Die Zielgruppe sind Enthusiasten, die ihren eigenen High-End PC bauen und sich im Corsair Universum bewegen. 64GB braucht ebenfalls kein normaler Mensch, der seine Office Anwendungen laufen l√§sst oder sich einen Gaming Rechner zusammenstellt.Kritik: Corsair w√§re gut damit beraten, an der Stabilit√§t von iCUE zu arbeiten. Manchmal werden die Riegel unter Windows 10 auf einen Asus MB nicht richtig erkannt (ich spreche hier von der RGB Steuerung) und werden in iCUE mit einem roten Warndreieck angezeigt. Dann hilft es nur iCUE zu beenden, den Lightning Service (Dienst) neu zu starten und iCUE erneut aufzurufen. Gerade im Zusammenspiel mit Aura (Asus) ist mir das sehr unangenehm aufgefallen. Die Hersteller schieben sich das Problem nat√ºrlich gegenseitig in die Schuhe.Fazit: Wer 64GB C16er Speicher mit vier Riegeln "braucht", RGB mit iCUE cool findet und daf√ºr bereit ist eine Niere zu verkaufen ist hier gut beraten. Alle anderen schauen sich nach g√ºnstigeren Modulen um, die √§hnliche Performance zu einem viel g√ºnstigeren Preis bieten.', 'Slipped straight in without any issues and worked first time, looks great as well. Definately recommended if this is compatible with your mother board', "One of the red LEDs was defective and the square always displayed the wrong shade of colour - an unacceptable level of QC at this price point.The CMT64GX4M4K3600C16 I received was v4.31 with Samsung B-Die. The semi-stable maximum overclock I was able to achieve was 3800 MT/s 16-16-16-34-300 dual-rank quad-channel at 1.45 V on an X299 Dark. I didn't bother stabilizing it as I decided to return it. This dual-rank kit would not POST at 4000 MT/s with any voltage or timings - it always hung at POST code EE. I can do 4000 MT/s 16-16-16-34-275 single-rank quad-channel at 1.45 V on the same system. The RAM ran extremely hot at 1.45 V - it hit 61 C just booting to the desktop, which was probably the reason for the infrequent errors in MemTest86's random pattern test at 3800 MT/s.This kit makes no sense at its current price when the F4-3600C16Q-64GTZR / F4-3600C16Q-64GTZN is $499, and F4-3600C14Q-64GTZN is $589. I bought it only because I wanted iCUE integrated RGB and it was discounted to $666. There's no justification for the 60% or so markup over the competition.", 'Excelentes memorias corsair dominator, despues de 15 horas intentando encontrar el modo donde activar el XMP, por fin pude hacerlas correr a 3200 MHz ! A buena hora pude correr el ROCK SIMULATOR a 200 cuadros por segundo y abrir el paint en segundos.PROS: Ya traen las lucesitas instaladasPROS 2: Las lucesitas hacen que tu pc parezca un antro, con la nostalgia de estar encerrado.CONS: no necesitaba 64gb de memoria, pero no habia kits de 4  a 8gb, yo queria ver las lucesitas en un kit de 4, tampoco traen manual de instalacion.', "XMP did not work out of the box, and this is with an X570 Aurous XTREME and a 3950x. Product: CORSAIR CMW32GX4M2Z3200C16 Vengeance RGB Pro 32GB (2x16GB) DDR4 3200 (PC4-25600) C16 AMD Optimized Memory kit, Black, 32 Gb
Reviews:
["Tout d'abord, ce sont bien des Z3200. Puces Micron D-die. Timing de base (non xmp) 2666@1.2v jedec 18-18-18-43 ou xmp 3200 16-18-18-36Test fait sur X99-UD4 et X99P-SLI avec un 5930K-1ere chose a savoir : ce CPU est fait pour du 2133Mhz.  le profil non xmp 2666 ne boot pas windows, sauf √† tweaker les voltages, timings et autres. Un vrai casse-t√™te. En 3200 XMP √ßa passe (voltage √† 1.43 en auto attention ! ) en manuel, faut tout trifouiller aussi.-2eme chose : j'ai pris 2 kits (soit 2x32x2 (=64Go Bah oui, quad channel quoi ! ) j'ai eu 4 num√©ro de s√©rie qui se suivent (17-18-19-20) donc c'est bon signe sur la compatibilit√©. Eh bah non, √ßa ne boot pas en 3200 (bios). Par contre, en BLCK 102-103, l√† √ßa boot. (donc √ßa donne 3266 ou 3300Mhz). C'est apparemment connu de cette s√©rie de CPU. avant skylake, au dessus de 3Ghz c'est compliqu√© √† stabiliser.J'ai jou√© avec les timing en ayant bien resserr√© les primaires, secondaires tertiaires, Il y a du potentiel (mais pas trop). Je dois investiguer plus avant, car memtest86 est assez impardonnable au test 7 et 8.donc pour les timings de base en dual channel xmp 3200 sur aida64 (Lire-Ecrire-Copie-Latence (en ns)) :45000-25500-40600-63en quad channel xmp 3230mhz : 55800-51400-59000-65et avec des timing l√©g√®rement am√©lior√©s (dont tCCD_L √† 6) : 57000-54250-68000-62.5Je n'ai pas trop essay√© de pousser √† 3400mhz et plus, le X99 n'aime pas √ßa, surtout en quad.Hors synth√©tique sur les chargements de gros assets comme DCS world, je gagne 10% de vitesse en moyenne sur une mission complexe (100=>90sec) , et les chargements brutaux en-jeu ne font plus de freeze (par rapport au 2133). Sur Arma 3 et d'autres gros jeux gourmands en RAM, le CPU rentre plus en compte.niveau couleur : je suis pas fana de RGB, mais j'avoue √ßa claque. je varie la couleur selon la temp√©rature, sinon vous pouvez faire a peu pr√®s n'importe quel drapeau :-D", "These new Vengeance RGB RAM are much better than the previous versions. The colours and patterns are much better. I am able to reach 3200 MHz, although that's based off the motherboard. I use these two sticks of ram with two dummy sticks so all four memory slots have RGB. My room looks like a rainbow now.", "Sulle mie macchine ho da sempre montato RAM marchiate Corsair, essendomi trovato sempre bene con questo produttore. Non mi soffermo pi√π di tanto sulle prestazioni, poich√® sono in linea di massima identiche alle Vengeance LP, quindi ottime. Quello che colpisce di queste memorie √® lo stile: sono bellissime da vedere e da configurare, grazie al software iCUE di Corsair. Se all'interno del proprio computer sono installati altri dispositivi RGB interfacciabili con iCUE, √® possibile creare dei giochi di luce spettacolari, ad un prezzo di poco superiore rispetto alle Vengeance LP. L'unica nota negativa sono le dimensioni: non essendo low profile, l'installazione di dissipatori molto grandi pu√≤ risultare problematica, nessun problema chiaramente se si usa un AIO a liquido. Confermo compatibilit√† con CPU AMD Ryzen 3700x e ASUS X570 TUF Gaming (Wi-Fi).", "The media could not be loaded.
                



\xa0The Corsair RAM works well in my ASUS mobo - I purchased it because it was on the approved list. I was able to set up BIOS to use the XMP setting and ended up with 3200 speed. No problems with memory and ran memtest with no errors. For the ARGB, I don't know whether it's the Corsair iCUE software or the ASUS Armoury Crate software, but I had a lot of problems getting them to sync up. I had to install and reinstall several times in a particular order for it to recognize the Corsair and sync with the Mobo. I would give 5 stars for the RAM and 3 for the software.I didn't try overclocking the memory beyond the rated speed.", "Good budget ddr.  No issues with my amd x570 chipset board and amd ryzen 9 3900xt setup. Personally I dislike rgb. But got a nice black friday price so I won't complainusing iCUE software you can control RGB lighting pattern.  You can completely turn it off too.  My favorite mode is the temperature color mode where you can select GREEN-->RED gradient scheme to indicate CPU temperature visual.  You also can select which temperature points that is LOW temp (green)  MID temp (orangy)  and HIGH TEMP RED thresholds.  It makes RBG actually USEFUL other than just pretty colors.", "First, I'm not a gamer, so look elsewhere for a gaming review/feedback.Currently in the midst of setting up the system, but if you plan to use a cooling solution such as a Hyper 212 LED, you should plan on rotating the seating for it to fit.  These sticks of RAM will prevent the default configuration of the  Hyper 212 from being fastened to the socket/motherboard.", "Fitted in a set with a Ryzen 7 3700X, this memory seems decent so far. I haven't messed too much with the machine but it runs really quickly. I plan to run a few VMs so opted for more, faster memory.RGB lights are really nice. They're really bright so I'm kinda glad I've got a dark tinted window on my case to dull the brightness a little... but the Corsair iCUE software works really well to play with the settings. Links up well with my other RGB components like Corsair H100i RGB Platinum", 'No vi por ninguna parte que era el modelo optimizado para AMD, as√≠ que me toco devolverlo.Poco puedo a√±adir.', 'Gekauft F√ºr Meine Gaming pc mit eine 3700x ryzen und tuf gaming + x570 asus mainboard, funktioniert wie erwartet , mit xmp 3200 cl 16  ( 16-18-18-36-54 xmp , und 2666 mhz ohne xmp) , mit sehr gute rgb Beleuchtung  und Effekten alles via iCUE software Einstellbar  . ich habe 2 x 16 gb gekauft und eine Beleuchtung kit ( also schaut genau wie normale Module aber ohne ddr4 speicher , dummy  ) in gesamt 4 stk wie in foto zum sehen ist . werde ich wieder kaufen !', "These RAM sticks worked great for my newest PC build! Corsair's RBG was very easy to integrate with my ASUS ROG STRIX motherboard, my RGB AMD Wraith cooler, and my case's RGB. This RAM will allow me to overclock my AMD RYZEN 3700X and not be bottlenecked by the RAM. If you would rather use a more powerful CPU like 3800X or better, I would personally recommend spending a little more to get 3400 or 3600 memory."]

Product: PNY 16GB (2x8GB) XLR8 Gaming DDR4 2666MHz (PC-4-21300) Desktop Memory Kit - (MD16GK2D4266616XR)
Reviews: ['Deux barrettes de cette RAM install√©es sur une carte m√®re Asus Z170 Pro Gaming.Difficult√© dans un premier temps √† faire fonctionner l\'ordinateur car ce mod√®le de carte m√®re est pour le moins sensible mais j\'ai fini par trouver un r√©glage du BIOS satisfaisant et depuis, aucun probl√®me, ordinateur parfaitement stable.Cet ordinateur √©quip√© d\'un processeur Intel i7 7700 n\'est plus du "dernier cri" mais il reste encore performant et les deux barrettes ont apport√© un petit suppl√©ment de puissance, √† la fois par une petite acc√©l√©ration de la m√©moire vive et par l\'augmentation de sa taille pass√©e ici de 8 √† 16 Go.Il a √©t√© n√©cessaire de "mettre les mains dans le cambouis" avec ma Z170 mais √ßa valait le coup, le r√©sultat est √† la hauteur et je n\'ai plus eu √† y toucher ensuite.Jouer √† remplir au maximum la m√©moire vive en lan√ßant une kyrielle de programmes peut finir par faire ralentir l\'ordinateur car cette quantit√© de 16 Go est assez confortable (pour un particulier, je pr√©cise) et permet d\'en lancer beaucoup en m√™me temps y compris avec un jeu video en m√™me temps, mais il ne plante pas, chacune des applis r√©pond correctement, peut √™tre ferm√©e "proprement", etc. bref quoi que je fasse la machine reste stable.Donc attention, avant d\'acheter cette RAM il faut bien v√©rifier que la carte m√®re destin√©e √† la recevoir peut fonctionner avec. Si c\'est le cas alors cette RAM se montre parfaitement efficace.', 'I used this in my ASUS Pro motherboard where Crucial Ballistix RAM does run at 2666 Mhz, 1.2 V in JEDEC.As the manufacturer answered in the Q&A here as well as their own support people told me over the email - this RAM does NOT run at 2666 Mhz as the SPD default.They lied - because I see in the BIOS that the JEDEC default for this memory - which I confirmed over & over again is 2133 Mhz and not 2666 Mhz which you will only get with XMP which my motherboard does not support.I tested with just one RAM stick - after removing all the existing ones to be sure.', 'Been using PNY Ram since my very first build and that was 20 some years ago, I love the company the sticks always feel solid and quality and have never had an issue with one.', 'Article de qualit√©,correctement livr√©,la carte mere a un tr√®s bon designe  les performances de la carte mere son excellente et convienne pour le gaming je recommande !Attention juste pour ceux qui utilisent des procceseur intel cette carte mere est pour les procceseur amd', "I ordered these specifically because they claimed to be Dual Rank, and they are clearly single rank.PNY I'm case you read this, Dual Rank means there's 2 sets of memory chips, on either side of the pcb, if it's only on one side, that's called single rank, I think you meant to put Dual Channel though any ram is dual channel if your motherboard supports it, can't believe I have to explain technology to a tech company. I received single rank 2666mhz DDR4 with the same timings as the sticks I already had making these actually useless compared to what I already had.I highly suggest you change your marketing for this line of products before you get yourselves sued for false advertising and or changing your product without marketing that you did.", 'Ordered the 16 GB set with two 8 GB sticks as this matched the RAM I was already using. Installed both sticks and got a DRAM error on my motherboard. Removed one and it fired right up. Removed that one and put the other one in place and it failed again. Pulled out all my RAM and used just the problematic stick and it failed again. So out of two RAM sticks, I only got one working stick.', 'I maxed out my PC with all XLR8 gaming parts great bang for your buck!', 'ÂçäBTO„Å™PC„ÅÆÂ§ßÂπÖ„Å™„Éê„Éº„Ç∏„Éß„É≥„Ç¢„ÉÉ„Éó„Å´Ë≥ºÂÖ•„ÄÇÂçäÂπ¥Ëøë„Åè‰Ωø„Å£„Å¶Êù•„Åæ„Åó„Åü„Åå„ÄÅ„Éí„Éº„Éà„Ç∑„É≥„ÇØ„ÅåÂäπ„ÅÑ„Å¶„Çã„ÅÆ„Åã„ÄÅ„É™„ÉÜ„Éº„É´„ÇØ„Éº„É©„Éº„ÅÆ„Åø„Åß„Åô„Åå„ÄÅÂ§è„ÅÆÊó•„Åß„ÇÇ40‚ÑÉ„ÇíË∂ä„Åà„ÇãÊÑü„Åò„ÅØ„ÅÇ„Çä„Åæ„Åõ„Çì„Åß„Åó„Åü„ÄÇ„Åì„ÅÆ„Åæ„ÅæWindows11„Å´Êõ¥Êñ∞„Åó„Å¶„ÇÇÁÑ°‰∫ã„Å´Èï∑ÊåÅ„Å°„Åó„Å¶„ÇÇ„Çâ„ÅÑ„Åü„ÅÑ„Åß„ÅôÔºÅ', 'Presentation', 'Installed in an IBuyPower 960, and it worked great. Product: Crucial 4GB DDR3L 1333MHz SODIMM Memory for Mac Module (CT4G3S1339M)
Reviews: ['Upgraded my late 2011 15" MBP from 8GB to this 16GB RAM (together with an internal upgrade to SSD), and it\'s working well. RAM was easy to remove and easy to install ‚Äî just have to get the angle right when slotting it in.', 'Gave an ancient (2012) Mac a new lease of life - purchase of new computer can now be deferred!', 'tous fonctionne nickel', 'Pacchetto e spedizione niente da dire... Ma competenza del venditore ben poca... per lavoro ho dovuto aggiornare un pc e alla semplice domanda se queste ram fossero specifiche per prodotti apple o potevano andare bene anche per altri pc con stessi requisiti tecnici la risposta √® stata " non disponiamo di questa informazione"...visto che molti acquistano tramite le recensioni son qui ad avvisare che chi avesse dubbi se comprare o meno queste ram per affidarsi a crucial... le ram arrivano ben sigillate con una particolarit√†... in descrizione viene scritto volt 1,5 peccato che son da 1.3 ..comunque possono essere utilizzate su prodotti e portatili che soddisfino gli stessi requisiti tecnici... quindi 1333 mhz CL9  pc3 10600 2Rx8.. per ora funzionano da diverse ore e bene ... ma vi terr√≤ aggiornati.... (installate su sony vaio non recente)', "I watched the performance of my MacBook Pro 13 in (late 2011) degrade slowly over a period of time. It seems every time the OS was upgraded, the performance went down.. I'm currently on Sierra .. and after a year or so, I had enough.. I looked at the Activity Monitor to see what was happening and noticed that the memory swap used was relatively high. I knew at that point it was time to upgrade the memory. I realized that when we originally bought the MacBook, 4Gb was sufficient, but over time with the OS upgrades, new software added, it could no longer handle it.I checked the compatibility online to make sure I got the right one, and then placed an order through Amazon. I was excited when it came and quickly shut down my laptop to install the RAM. Installation was very easy and took less than a minute (you will need a small phillips screwdriver to remove the panel of the laptop, to expose the motherboard). Turned it back on, and got the dreaded three beeps. I went back, removed the RAM, and reinserted.. and tried again.. and again, the three beeps... Removed the new RAM, and re-inserted the old memory and everything was fine.I checked the package and model numbers, and everything was correct. At that point, I thought to myself.. there is something wrong. I returned it and re-ordered a new set. Repeated the steps, and this time, upon startup, no beeps!Everything seemed more responsive, and applications opened quickly. I check the Activity Monitor, and looked at the memory swap - a big fat Zero!!!I'll have to remind myself to check the Activity Monitor over time periodically. If memory usage ever creeps up to 7 Gb, it will be time to upgrade to 16 Gb.", "Three years ago I took over our son's 2011 MacBook Pro that he used through high school and three years of college. I needed my own computer for general internet work and an occasional document or web meeting. The computer was very slow. I contacted the school IT department that provided the computer. They suggested formatting the HD which would erase thousands of dollars worth of software. I decided to double the memory. The manual said 8GB is the max but people were reporting they were putting in 16 GB. Upon further reading I realized I had a 13-inch and the people putting in four times the original memory had 15 and 17-inch screens. The computer is runs like a new machine. I just ordered a firewire cable and plan to convert all of my 8mm videos to DVDs and get into Photoshop and other media programs. This is preferable to spending over $1,000 just for the need for speed! Fifteen minutes to install. I needed to be careful not to lose the screws. Get these memory cards before they stop making them.", "I'm blown away. I have 10 apps up and running flawlessly and 13 Chrome tabs open as I type this review. I can't believe how much faster it has made my iMac run when operating with multiple apps running. I have been using the 4GB of RAM since 2011 and didn't even realize how easy this would be to upgrade. I was ready to trash this desktop and get a new one. Before installing the extra 8GB of RAM (4+4), the computer would freeze up if I dared open more than 3 apps. Work was painstakingly slow. I'm tempted to replace the 4GB (2+2) with another 8GB just for the added RAM now. But I'll see how this goes.One warning. Inserting the new RAM took a serious push. I was afraid of breaking the chips or that I was doing something wrong. I had to use a towel to put over my finger when snapping the new RAM into place, because the edge was hurting my finger, but as long as they're lined up right, trust they'll fit. You just have to force them. Worked flawlessly. Anyone can do this.", 'It took a couple of months after my iMac computer began crashing frequently before an Apple hardware diagnostic test identified the problem as being a faulty memory module. The same test a few weeks earlier failed to find any hardware problems. I discovered there are many international manufacturers listed on the Internet for this part but no store in Canada keeps it in stock. A few online stores including Amazon all said shipping would take a few weeks. I found instructions from Apple on how to replace the original memory modules with these new Crucial memory modules. The problem of my iMac computer frequently crashing is now fixed. Through testing I found one of the original 4GB memory modules is okay so now I have 3 x 4GB = 12GB installed. In contrast to all of the online advice and reviews I did not notice any improvement in the speed of my iMac by upgrading from 8GB to 12GB. The Apple hardware diagnostic test full version that is needed to test the memory modules takes a few hours to run. Apple evaluated the trade-in value of my iMac as being $99. These new Crucial memory modules with tax cost me more than the trade-in value of my iMac. I hope my iMac continues to work for a few more years now that these new Crucial memory modules have fixed the frequent crashing problem.', 'iMac 21.5-inch, Mid 2010, 3.2 GHz Intel Core i3OS X Yosemite 10.10.1Wanted to upgrade from the base 4GB of RAM provided by Apple. Looking for better performance. Interesting problem upon installation.Attempt One:  Original two 2GB DIMMs were in BANK 0/DIMM1 and BANK 1/DIMM1. Added the new Crucial 4 GB DIMMs to open slots for BANK 0/DIMM0 and BANK 1/DIMM0. Upon startup, the iMac blared the warning horn. Annoying sound. Had to power down holding the power button.Attempt Two:  Swapped one each of the two sets so the DIMMs were in the same banks. Once again the horn alarm upon startup. Power down . . .Attempt Three:  Loaded only the new two 4GB DIMMs in BANK 0/DIMM1 and BANK 1/DIMM1. Booted up fine. ‚ÄúAbout this Mac‚Äù showed 8GB total RAM. Success with new Crucial RAM.Attempt Four:  Keeping the two new Crucial 4GB DIMMs in BANK 0/DIMM1 and BANK 1/DIMM1, loaded the two original 2GB DIMMs into the DIMM0 banks. Booted up. Worked fine. ‚ÄúAbout this Mac‚Äù showed 12GB total RAM. This was the intended end goal. Success with both old Apple/Samsung RAM and new Crucial RAM.Odd that the old RAM had to be relocated to the open slots. Specs between old and new did match, DDR3 1333 MHz. Have always had success with Crucial RAM in both PCs and Macs. Will continue to recommend Crucial.Hope this helps other do-it-yourselfers.', "This crucial ram works great in my computer. Used to upgrade a 9 year old laptop. Its like having a new (old looking) laptop! Very happy as it keeps an old computer out of landfill and saves me from having to spring $$ for a new computer.This is nothing to do with the quality of the ram, but be aware that the tool on the Crucial ram website that tells you what ram to use was incorrect in my case. It told me to use 1600mhz ram but the specs on my computer call for 1333mhz. Crucial website said 1333mhz wouldn't work for my computer ,when it was in fact the correct oem spec. The ram Crucial's online tool said was correct wouldn't have worked. Be aware of this and check on the manufacturer site of your computer or elsewhere on the web (forums etc) for correct ram specs before ordering."]

Product: Powerbuilt 648539 Computer Memory Keeper
Reviews: ['I was changing my car battery and didn‚Äôt want all my settings to reset. I also didn‚Äôt want to pay for the more expensive code reader plug as you need a battery for that thing. Replaced the battery took about an hour and my radio settings were just fine. My fuel consumption did reset so not sure if that is supposed to reset regardless.', "As another reviewer has indicated, you must have a ''hot'' lighter socket or turn the ignition keyto ''accessory''.  I disconnected the battery for a few minutes on my 2006 Corolla to clean a terminal.When I reconnected the battery all my presets were unchanged and the computer did not have to ''relearn'' settings.", "2014 Subaru Forester. Turned off radio, gps and fan. Put in fresh 9v max battery which read about 9.7 volts. Disconnected battery and then found that cable terminal was corroded in rear so had to go  to auto parts store to get a new one.  9v was probably left powering stuff for 2 hours. After installing new car battery, radio presets were lost.  9v battery was down to 8.3 v.  Maybe 2hr is too long a time. Also I did see a spark when I accidently hit cable end with screwdriver shorting it out. There are no instructions of information on how long it will keep memory up.  Don't know if the quick short also was an issue. Writing this to warn anyone interested to find out those issues before attempting if you might have issues getting the car battery back in quickly.", 'It works perfectly.  Before disconnecting the car battery, I plugged the device (with 9-volt battery attached) into the cigarette lighter port and turned the ignition key to the ACCESSORY MODE (where radio and windshield and windshield wipers will work withouttheenging running).  Then the car abttery was removed and reolaced.  When done, all my radio settings and everything else were still there.  Nothing was lost.', "Doesn't work on Toyota,Most likely not going to work on import makes . Will update if find out this work on certain make and model.", "Haven't used it yet but looks OK", 'I bought this for a 2011 Toyota FJ Crusier. I was skeptical this would work. I turned the key to the accessory position and plugged in the unit. I disconnected and removed my old battery then went to the auto parts store to get a new battery. The time between disconnecting my old battery and installing the new battery was about an hour. I was very impressed this unit worked.  I was very happy that I did not lose any radio settings or computer settings.Pros:  Worked as advertised.Cons:  No indicator lights to show the unit is on or connected.Would recommend to others.', "I just used this while changing the battery in my Lexus GX470.  I plugged it in (with a new 9V), turned the ignition switch to Accessory and replaced the vehicle's battery in about 20 minutes.  My vehicle's seat memory and radio presets were remembered, which were the most important items for me.  It didn't save the clock time and I still needed to reset the auto up/down function on all the windows, but that was simple & fast to do.Overall, buying this memory keeper was well worth it.SEPTEMBER 2017 UPDATE: Just used this when changing the battery in my Lexus LS430 and it worked perfectly. The memory keeper was plugged in for 10 minutes with the car key switched to accessory while I changed the battery. Seat memory, radio stations and window settings were all remembered.", 'I use this to hold the settings in my car when the battery is disconnected (replaced, clean terminals, whatever).  Obviously has to be connected to the 12v accessory plug.  I also got an 8 AA battery holder with the standard 9v battery connection so my setup will supply 12v.  The accessory plug has to be hot for this to work so the key may have to be in the accessory position.  My car has one that is always on even if the car is off.', "Had to replace my auto battery, and this little thing kept my clock, radio presets, phone synch, and all other memory settings from erasing.Use a good 9v, and don't expect it to hold things for hours."]

Reviews: ["With Crucial/Micron no longer producing Ballistix RAM, I struggled to find a matched pair for my 2x8GB to upgrade to 32GB, so I set about looking for 32GB of entirely new 3600MHz CL16 RAM.Not wanting to pay a G.Skill premium, which was over 60% more at the time, I settled on this. Works perfectly on the default XMP profile to get the rated timings in an Asus ROG Strix B550 F-Gaming, firstly with my 5600X for two months and later a 5800X3D for the past month or so.It's been rock solid in terms of stability and, whilst the timings beyond CL are not as tight as the Ballistix it replaced on paper, there's no perceivable difference in performance (aside from having more of it of course).I'm still sad about the loss of Crucial Ballistix, as it was always hard to beat for price/performance, but I've been very happy with this purchase.", 'Usadas sin problemas ni incidencia alguna en su  perfil XMP a su velocidad nativa de 3200mhz en una placa Asus ROG B560i.
